term_definitions.items: A scale to describe the onset and progression of pubertal changes.
Default, unspecified point in time event which may be explicitly defined in a template or at run-time.
The stages for development in male genitals.
The stages for breast development in young women.
The stages for pubic hair development in females and males.
Enlargement of scrotum and testes; scrotal skin reddens and changes in texture.
Enlargement of penis (length at first); further growth of testes.
Increased size of penis with growth in breadth and development of glans; testes and scrotum larger, scrotal skin darker.
Breast bud stage with elevation of breast and papilla; enlargement of areola.
Further enlargement of breast and areola; no separation of their contour.
Areola and papilla form a secondary mound above level of breast.
Mature stage: projection of papilla only, related to recession of areola.
Prepubertal (the pubic area may have vellus hair, similar to that of forearms).
Sparse growth of long, slightly pigmented hair, straight or curled, at base of penis or along labia.
Darker, coarser and more curled hair, spreading sparsely over junction of pubes.
Hair adult in type, but covering smaller area than in adult; no spread to medial surface of thighs.
Adult in type and quantity, with horizontal upper border.
